  <p class="">One of the most anticipated VRChat features is now live: Groups!</p><p class="">Not sure what Groups is? In short, Groups is a new system that will make it easier for everyone to find the coolest communities and creations VRChat has to offer.&nbsp;</p><p class="">They‚Äôre such a big feature for VRChat, that we‚Äôve gone ahead and dedicated a new Developer Update Video to them! Check it out:</p>





















  
  








  <iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="//www.youtube.com/embed/b6c_kDRJG2A?wmode=opaque" width="854" frameborder="0" height="480"></iframe>




  <p class="">There are genuinely so many unique and incredible communities in VRChat: people come in here to fly jets together, explore worlds, make music, party, have virtual car meets, simply hang out and chat, and of course, make cool stuff together.</p><p class="">Yet as it stands, it can be a little difficult to actually find all of those people!</p><p class="">Groups goes a long way to fix that, making it easier for both new and existing users to find communities that interest them, as well as making those very same communities a lot easier to run.</p><p class="">Now, a new player might come into VRChat, see someone‚Äôs group tag ‚Äì say FLIGHT ‚Äì and then ask about it. The person who is in the group might tell the user that they meet up with their group a few times a week to do dogfighting in VRChat. All of a sudden, that new user is being sucked into a community they never knew existed. On top of that, they now have a chance of being exposed to an entirely different group of people ‚Äì all of which could be potential new friends!</p><p class="">Maybe you have a large community as it is ‚Äì maybe running out of a service like Discord. In large communities, it can be hard to know when folks are online, or when something is going on. Now, though, you can just sign in, look at your group, and join on someone that‚Äôs online and in an open Group instance!</p><p class="">Groups are incredibly powerful ‚Äì we see them as equally vital for VRChat as, say, avatar and user-created worlds.</p><h3>The Groups Launch Process</h3><p class="">We think that Groups is going to be a massive change to VRChat ‚Äì one that‚Äôs unlike anything that‚Äôs happened to the community before. While we ultimately believe this is a good thing, we want to be very cautious with how we release this particular feature.</p><p class="">There are also a few technical challenges that prevent us from releasing everything all at once, like we‚Äôd usually do. To get around this, we‚Äôll be releasing Groups piecemeal in stages.</p>





















  
  














































  

    
  
    

      

      
        <figure class="
              sqs-block-image-figure
              intrinsic
            "
        >
          
        
        

        
          
            
          
            
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <img data-stretch="false" data-image="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png" data-image-dimensions="1910x1071" data-image-focal-point="0.5,0.5" alt="" data-load="false" elementtiming="system-image-block" src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=1000w" width="1910" height="1071" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, (max-width: 767px) 100vw, 100vw" onload="this.classList.add(&quot;loaded&quot;)" srcset="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=100w 100w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=300w 300w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=500w 500w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=750w 750w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=1000w 1000w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=1500w 1500w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/9b9de91d-6894-4cad-9e1c-3e552ce12a8a/timeline.png?format=2500w 2500w" loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-loader="sqs">

            
          
        
          
        

        
      
        </figure>
      

    
  


  





  <p class="">The first stage is what is being pushed live today. It contains what we consider to be the most important, foundational features Groups needs to function.</p><p class="">In the next stage, which should arrive a short time after the initial release, we intend to add in search, as well as respond to the aforementioned user feedback. From that point on, we plan to iterate and add in more features, some of which we‚Äôve already planned out, and some of which are dependent on the user response to Groups.&nbsp;</p><p class="">We‚Äôre a little leery about giving exact timelines here, but we‚Äôre fairly comfortable saying that there shouldn‚Äôt be months between each of these releases. Of course, we‚Äôre also pushing the first stage of Groups right before the holidays. Assuming everything goes smoothly, that means we‚Äôll have very little time between release and our holiday break. That means that there might be more time between the first and second stage than we might want, but we should hopefully pick up the pace once we‚Äôre all back in the proverbial office!</p><p class="">After the second stage, we‚Äôll be adding in a few more foundational features, as well as implementing as much user feedback as we can. It‚Äôs worth noting, though, that while we‚Äôll be doing our best to address feedback in each stage, our focus will primarily be getting what we see as core features out the door first.&nbsp;</p><p class="">With that out of the way, let‚Äôs get into the details!</p><h3>How Groups Works</h3><p class="">The Groups system allows you to make‚Ä¶ Groups! Anyone with VRChat+ will be able to make up to three new groups via the VRChat website. While you‚Äôll eventually be able to do this in-app, for now, it‚Äôs done via the website only. Building a complex UI takes time, and we didn‚Äôt want it to hold up the launch ‚Äì basically, think of this as early access Groups creation.</p><p class="">Before we go further: yes, you will need VRChat+ to make a group ‚Äì but you won‚Äôt need it to join one. We want everyone to be able to use Groups, we just don‚Äôt want a massive flood of new groups right out the gate. We‚Äôre unsure as of now if this restriction will stay forever, or if it will be temporary.</p>





















  
  



<iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/joyfulbogushyena?hd=1&amp;controls=0" width="100%" frameborder="0" height="100%"></iframe>


  <p class="">When you make a group, you‚Äôll have to pick its name, as well as a few other things ‚Äì like an identifier, description, group icon, banner, and if it‚Äôs public or private.</p><p class="">All groups will have both a name and an identifier. A group name can be whatever you choose ‚Äì following the <a href="https://hello.vrchat.com/community-guidelines">Community Guidelines</a>, of course. It isn‚Äôt unique, though, and multiple groups can have the same name.</p><p class="">The identifier, though, must be unique! The identifier consists of three to six characters in a string that you choose, followed by a randomly assigned set of four numbers. </p>





















  
  














































  

    
  
    

      

      
        <figure class="
              sqs-block-image-figure
              intrinsic
            "
        >
          
        
        

        
          
            
          
            
                
                
                
                
                
                
                
                <img data-stretch="false" data-image="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png" data-image-dimensions="2197x1237" data-image-focal-point="0.5,0.5" alt="" data-load="false" elementtiming="system-image-block" src="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=1000w" width="2197" height="1237" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, (max-width: 767px) 100vw, 100vw" onload="this.classList.add(&quot;loaded&quot;)" srcset="https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=100w 100w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=300w 300w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=500w 500w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=750w 750w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=1000w 1000w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=1500w 1500w, https://images.squarespace-cdn.com/content/v1/5f0770791aaf57311515b23d/10b3f80a-ef8f-40ec-9e54-7c2d4131d137/discrimnator.png?format=2500w 2500w" loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-loader="sqs">

            
          
        
          
        

        
      
        </figure>
      

    
  


  





  <p class="">This is often&nbsp;referred to as a Discriminator. Unlike the group name, the combination of the group‚Äôs identifier and its discriminator IS unique. If you‚Äôve used other services where people are likely to have similar names, you probably recognize this setup.</p><p class="">After that, you‚Äôll need to enter in a description for your group which will be displayed to other users, provided your group is public. You‚Äôll then have to pick how people will join your group. Will you allow anyone to join, or will you require people to request permission? Or maybe you want it to be invite only?</p><p class="">Additionally, you can add a set of rules. We want Groups to be able to set expectations for how they expect their members to behave, and we want group members to see the reasons they might get in trouble.&nbsp;</p><p class="">We expect that some groups may want to set special rules ‚Äì for example, a roleplaying group may require that users be in-character in certain situations. Of course, the VRChat <a href="https://hello.vrchat.com/legal">Terms of Service</a> and <a href="https://hello.vrchat.com/community-guidelines">Community Guidelines</a> ALWAYS apply to everyone using VRChat, but these rules let groups manage themselves more effectively and openly.</p><p class="">Finally, individual groups can be set to private or public. Private groups cannot be searched for, and you must be invited to join. Public groups can be set as invite-only, request to join, or open for everyone to join.</p><p class="">As a note, once you‚Äôve set a group to one, you won‚Äôt be able to switch it to the other. Public groups will always be public, and private groups will always be private. We‚Äôre doing this primarily for privacy reasons ‚Äì for example, if you‚Äôre in a group you think is private, you probably wouldn‚Äôt appreciate it too much if it suddenly went public!</p><h3>How Groups Makes Your Community Better</h3><p class="">If you already run a community, let‚Äôs talk about how Groups will make your life easier.</p><p class="">First, Groups will make it much easier for you to find new community members, likewise, it‚Äôll be much easier for them to find you.&nbsp;</p><p class="">To have others join your group, you can simply give them your identifier and discriminator. They can type it in on the groups tab in the main menu, or they can type it on on the website. Both ways will allow them to easily join your group (or request to join it, depending on how you have things setup).</p>





















  
  



<iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/anguishedadmiredcatfish?hd=1&amp;controls=0" width="100%" frameborder="0" height="100%"></iframe>


  <p class="">Likewise, every group will have a short link associated with it ‚Äì this link can then be handed to others so they can easily join your group. If you‚Äôve ever been invited to a Discord server, you generally know how this works.</p><p class="">While it won‚Äôt be in the initial release, we‚Äôre planning on incorporating a group search feature on both the VRChat website and in app. You‚Äôll be able to search for groups and join ones that are public and accepting requests. This won‚Äôt be in the initial release, but we‚Äôre anticipating that we‚Äôll turn search on during Stage 2.</p><p class="">Other users will also see members of your Group and be able to identify them. Users will be able to display their Group on their nametag, and you‚Äôll be able to see what public Groups people are in, in their profile. In VRChat, you‚Äôll be able to see information about the groups people are in, and decide if maybe you‚Äôre interested in joining.</p>





















  
  



<iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/determinednaivegoldenmantledgroundsquirrel?hd=1&amp;controls=0" width="100%" frameborder="0" height="100%"></iframe>


  <p class="">Maybe you visit a public flying world for the first time and see an ace pilot there owning the skies. You‚Äôd see in their nametag that they are part of a flying group. You could look at the description, see that they are a competitive flying group, and then ask to join ‚Äì suddenly you‚Äôd become aware of an entirely new activity in VRChat that people take part in!&nbsp;</p><p class="">But that‚Äôs just level one.</p><h4>Improving Community Organization</h4><p class="">We don‚Äôt just want it to be easier for folks with common interests to find each other ‚Äì we want to make it easier for communities to function, too.</p>





















  
  



<iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/talkativehardtofindcockroach?hd=1&amp;controls=0" width="100%" frameborder="0" height="100%"></iframe>


  <p class="">Groups will let you send out announcements ‚Äì notifications that appear to each member in the group. Later, we‚Äôd like to build an entire bulletin board system. You‚Äôll also have a group gallery, photos that everyone can see in the group.</p><p class="">Group members can also have permissions ‚Äì say, you can have members who can invite others, and those who can‚Äôt.</p><p class="">These are called roles ‚Äì and can be used for a variety of purposes. You might want to have a certain role for tour guides who can send announcements ‚Äì and maybe another for the purposes of moderation. We also think people will be able to do some real out-of-the-box thinking with roles, and we‚Äôre excited to see what people come up with.</p><p class="">As a note, there will be a limited number of roles at launch, but that might change over time depending on feedback.&nbsp;</p><h4>Group Instances and Presence</h4><p class="">Another major organizational feature that Groups adds is Group Instances.&nbsp;</p><p class="">Group instances are a new instance type that work similarly to something like Friends instances. If you make a Friends instance, everyone who has you on their Friends list will be able to join. With Group Instances, everyone in that particular group will be able to enter the instance.</p><p class="">We think that Group Instances will save people a lot of time who are hosting and running events. We also think they‚Äôll make a great and easy way for group members to hang out with each other.</p><p class="">That‚Äôs not the only way we want to bring Group members together, though.</p>





















  
  



<iframe scrolling="no" allowfullscreen src="https://gfycat.com/ifr/immaterialcheerfulcob?hd=1&amp;controls=0" width="100%" frameborder="0" height="100%"></iframe>


  <p class="">When you look at your groups page, you‚Äôll be able to see all of the instances your group members are in that you‚Äôre able to join. This way, you can immediately hop in and hang out with folks, even if you aren‚Äôt their friend yet!</p><h3>What‚Äôs Coming Next</h3><p class="">Groups is a huge system that we think is going to change VRChat forever.</p><p class="">Most of the features we‚Äôve mentioned today will be released in the first, groundwork stage of Groups. Others will be released ‚Äì along with polishing dictated by your feedback ‚Äì in the weeks following the launch of Groups. We want to push these updates out relatively quickly, as we‚Äôd like to get Groups up and running as fast as possible.&nbsp;</p><p class="">With that said, we‚Äôre also choosing to push Groups out now, instead of waiting until after the holidays. That means that there will be a bit of a break between stages, as we take time off to recuperate, rest, and reorganize. Once the holidays are over, though, we‚Äôll be right back at it, with the goal of pushing out as much as we can.</p><p class="">Likewise, in a month or two, we‚Äôll have another developer update where we‚Äôll be keeping you apprised of our progress, as well as what features we anticipate to bring to the Groups system next.</p><p class="">As previously mentioned, one of the reasons why we‚Äôre releasing Groups in stages is to incorporate feedback into the final product. To that end, we encourage users to provide us with their thoughts via the <a href="https://feedback.vrchat.com/groups">VRChat Feedback board</a>.</p><p class="">We‚Äôre excited to get Groups out there ‚Äì and we can‚Äôt wait for you to see what we‚Äôre working on next!</p>





















  
  



